= Use *tldr* for a brief version of  *man* =
%
= *procs* is a better *ps*! use *--json* for easier filtering =
%
= *rg* for a better *grep* =
  `rg pattern` to find all files contaning the pattern
  `-l` to list just the file name
  `--invert-match`
  `--files` list files that WOULD be searched
%
= *fd* to find files! =
  `fd "^pattern|other` downloads/
  `fd --extension jpg*`
  `fd . --exclude "glob*"`
%
= get json (or yaml!) keys with *yq* =
  yq keys file.json
%
= filter json/yaml with *yq* =
  cat file.json | yq '.[] | select((.key1=="value*") and (.key2 | tonumber >=  10))'
%
= `yq` output in different formats =
  yq '.[]' file.json --output-format json|yaml|csv
  yq '.[]' file.json -o json|yaml|csv
%
= neovim - do an action for the lines matching the pattern =
  :g/pattern/norm!dd
  :v/pattern/norm!dd  # reverse match!
%
= *dust* gives you a quick overview of disk usage, read bottom to top! =
%
= Use *duf* for getting disk usage information =
%
= *xh* can replace *curl* =
  xh get https://example.com header-name:header-value
  xh post https://example.com content-key=content-value
  echo {"something": true} | xh post https://httpbin.org/post
  xh get https://example.com --curl  # show curl equivalent
%
= *hyperfine* for benchmarking! =
  `hyperfine 'run this thing'
  `hyperfine --prepare 'do-this-before-each-run' 'then run this'`
%
= *presenter* makes presentations out of md files =
%
= port forwarding =
  `ssh -L [local_addr:port]:[remote_addr:port] user@host`
  the remote_addr can be the host's localhost *or* something else!
%
= *rmlint* is great for finding duplicates =
  `rmlint -k dir1 // dir2`
   this just flags what's duplicated in dir1 vs dir2
%
= *journalctl* show all logs for a given executable =
  `journalctl path/to/executable`
%
= *journalctl* user/system logs since some time =
  `journalctl --user --since "5 minutes ago" --until "1 minute ago"`
  `journalctl --system --since "5 minutes ago" --until "1 minute ago"`
%
= *journalctl* for a given unit =
  `journalctl --unit unit`
